mprove community relations instead of a majority clinging to insular isolated attitudes, the UK on a whole would be a better place. &#10;I lived on a US island, many kids were home schooled, it was a community of home schoolers, they interacted, they took sports programs up at the school, not all were religious based, although some were, some reintegrated into the school system and not once was there some big hullabaloo and over analysis of what parents were doing such that we see in this country. Where we tend to analyze everything to death, send in authorities that are not educated or have the wherewithall to understand the bigger picture. Sometimes I think the UK needs to get over itself and join the 21st century in regards to services and communities. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1065" language="en" documentId="1130" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Bluejil" date="29 July 2010 9:31am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6874860" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="5" thumbsDown="0" origId="1130" notes="" title="Home education: precious, not dangerous"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="218"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="219" end="435"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="436" end="1065"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>